For the sake of simplicity and clarity, we'll consider a one-dimensional system. This code demonstrates the behavior of the linearized system at steady-state values with set parameter values. Here is the MATLAB code:

``` matlab
% Parameters
L = 10;  % Length of the domain
D = 1;   % Diffusion coefficient for population
C = 1;   % Diffusion coefficient for information density
r = 0.1; % Growth rate
K = 100; % Carrying capacity
a = 0.01;% Information density effect

% Discretization
Nx = 100; % Number of grid points in x
dx = L/Nx;
x = linspace(0, L, Nx);

% Steady state values
y_star = K;
x_star = 0;

% Compute the Laplacian operator
Lap = sparse(Nx, Nx);
for i = 1:Nx
    j = i-1;
    if j==0
        j = Nx;
    end
    Lap(i, j) = 1;

    j = i+1;
    if j > Nx
        j = 1;
    end
    Lap(i, j) = 1;

    Lap(i, i) = -2;
end
Lap = Lap / dx^2;

% Evaluation of partial derivatives at steady state values
dfdy_star = -r * y_star / K;
dfdx_star = a;

dgdy_star = 0;
dgdx_star = r;

% Linearized system matrix
A = [D*Lap + dfdy_star*speye(Nx), dfdx_star*speye(Nx);
    dgdy_star*speye(Nx), C*Lap + dgdx_star*speye(Nx)];

% Compute eigenvalues
e = eig(full(A));

% Plot eigenvalues
real_e = real(e);
imag_e = imag(e);

figure;
plot(real_e, imag_e, 'o');
xlabel('Real part');
ylabel('Imaginary part');
title('Eigenvalues of the linearized system');
grid on;

% Check stability condition
if all(real_e < 0)
    disp('The system is stable.');
else
    disp('The system is unstable.');
end
```

Please note that this code considers constant coefficients and parameter values. You will need to adjust these values according to your specific problem or use input data to define them. This code primarily demonstrates how to set up the linearized system and compute its eigenvalues to determine the system's stability.

The code provided below sets up the logistic growth model for the population and solves the steady-states using the reaction terms. This code works for a one-dimensional spatial domain.

``` matlab
% Parameters
L = 10;    % Length of domain
Nx = 100;  % Number of grid points in x
x = linspace(0, L, Nx); % Spatial domain

D = 0.1;   % Diffusion coefficient for population
C = 0.1;   % Diffusion coefficient for information density
r = 1;     % Intrinsic growth rate
K = 100;   % Carrying capacity
a = 0.01;  % information density effect constant

% Initial conditions
y0 = K/2 * ones(1, Nx); % Initial population density
x0 = zeros(1, Nx);      % Initial information density

% Discretization in time
T = 50;      % Total simulation time
dt = 0.01;   % Time step
Nt = T/dt;   % Number of time steps
y = y0;
x = x0;

% Explicit time integration using Euler's method
for t = 1:Nt
    % Reaction terms
    fy = r*y.*(1 - y/K);
    gx = a*x;

    % Laplacian
    Dy = D * (circshift(y, [0 1]) - 2*y + circshift(y, [0 -1])) / (x(2) - x(1))^2;
    Dx = C * (circshift(x, [0 1]) - 2*x + circshift(x, [0 -1])) / (x(2) - x(1))^2;

    % Update the solution
    y = y + dt*(fy + Dy);  
    x = x + dt*(gx + Dx);
end

figure;
subplot(2, 1, 1);
plot(x, y); xlabel('x'); ylabel('y'); title('Population Density');
subplot(2, 1, 2);
plot(x, x); xlabel('x'); ylabel('x'); title('Information Density');

% Time-independent solution
y_steady = K * ones(1, Nx);
x_steady = zeros(1, Nx);

subplot(2, 1, 1);
hold on; plot(x, y_steady, 'r--'); xlabel('x'); ylabel('y'); legend('Numerical', 'Steady state');
subplot(2, 1, 2);
hold on; plot(x, x_steady, 'r--'); xlabel('x'); ylabel('x'); legend('Numerical', 'Steady state');
```

