Due to the complexity of the system of partial differential equations, it may be more efficient to use a finite difference method for numerical simulations. However, a simpler approach using ODE solver can be used for analyzing the stability of the steady-state solutions.

Here is an example code for Matlab:

%%%%%%% Parameters %%%%%%%%

% Intrinsic growth rate
r = 0.5;

% Carrying capacity
K = 1;

% Diffusion coefficient for population density
D = 0.1;

% Constant determining effect of information density
a = -0.2;

% Diffusion coefficient for information density
C = 0.05;

% Spatial domain
L = 20;
N = 100;

x = linspace(0, L, N+1);
y = linspace(0, K*2, N+1);

%%%%%%% Reaction terms %%%%%%%%

% Logistic growth model for population
f = @(y, x) r*y.*(1 - y/K);

% Linear model for information density
g = @(y, x) a*x;

%%%%%%% ODE system %%%%%%%%

% Define ODE system for y and x
dydt = @(t, yx) [f(yx(1), yx(2)); 0] + [D*diff(yx(1,:),2); 0];
dxdt = @(t, yx) [0; g(yx(1), yx(2))] + [0; C*diff(yx(2,:),2)];

% Define initial conditions
y0 = 0.5*ones(1, N+1);
x0 = zeros(1, N+1);
yx0 = [y0; x0];

% Define time range and solve ODE system
tspan = [0, 50];
[t, yx] = ode45(@(t, yx) [dydt(t, yx); dxdt(t, yx)], tspan, yx0);

%%%%%%% Plot results %%%%%%%%
subplot(2,1,1)
surf(x, t, yx(:,1:N+1))
xlabel('x')
ylabel('t')
zlabel('y')
title('Population density')

subplot(2,1,2)
surf(x, t, yx(:,N+2:end))
xlabel('x')
ylabel('t')
zlabel('x')
title('Information density')

