void drawIsland() {
    glEnable(GL_TEXTURE_2D);
    glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, islandTexture); // bind island texture

    // draw the base
    glPushMatrix();
    GLUquadricObj* base = gluNewQuadric();
    gluQuadricTexture(base, true);
    gluQuadricNormals(base, GLU_SMOOTH);
    gluDisk(base, 0.0f, 8.0f, 32, 1); // draw a disk for the main land
    gluCylinder(base, 0.0f, 5.5f, 2.0f, 32, 1); // draw a narrow cylinder to form the southeastern part of the island
    gluCylinder(base, 0.0f, 3.5f, 2.0f, 32, 1); // draw a narrower cylinder to form the northern and eastern parts of the island
    gluDeleteQuadric(base);
    glPopMatrix();

    // draw the mountain ranges
    glPushMatrix();
    GLUquadricObj* mountains = gluNewQuadric();
    gluQuadricTexture(mountains, true);
    gluQuadricNormals(mountains, GLU_SMOOTH);
    glTranslatef(0.0f, 0.0f, 1.0f); // move up from the base
    gluCylinder(mountains, 2.0f, 3.0f, 2.0f, 32, 1); // draw a taller cylinder for the main mountain range
    glTranslatef(0.0f, 0.0f, 2.0f); // move up to draw a second mountain range
    gluCylinder(mountains, 1.0f, 2.0f, 2.0f, 32, 1);
    gluDeleteQuadric(mountains);
    glPopMatrix();

    glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D);
}
```

In this code, the base of the island is created using a combination of gluDisk() and gluCylinder() calls to form the shape of Asia, with a narrower cylindrical shape to form the southeastern part of the island, and a narrower cylindrical shape to form the northern and eastern parts of the island. A texture is applied to the island base.

The mountain ranges are created using a separate GLUquadricObj object, with glTranslatef() used to move up and draw two different heights of cylinder. Finally, the texture is disabled using glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D).

